{"title_page": "Leonard C. Bailey", "text_new": "Leonard C. Bailey was a black business owner and inventor. He was born in 1825 to a free black family.<ref name=\"Blackpast\">[https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/bailey-leonard-c-1825-1918/ Blackpast: Leonard C. Bailey]</ref> Growing up in poverty, Bailey worked as a barber and built up a string of barbershops in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"Columbia1901\">{{cite book|author=Union League of the District of Columbia|title=The Twentieth Century Union League Directory: A Compilation of the Efforts of the Colored People of Washington for Social Betterment ... A Historical, Biographical, and Statistical Study of Colored Washington at the Dawn of the Twentieth Century and After a Generation of Freedom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mM0vAQAAMAAJ|year=1901}}</ref> \n\nHe invented and received patents for a series of devices, many designed for military or government use. These included a folding bed,<ref>{{cite patent |country=US|num=RE11830|title=Folding Bed|inventor=Leonard C. Bailey}}</ref> a rapid mail-stamping machine, a device to shunt trains to different tracks, and a hernia truss adopted into wide use by the U.S. military. Bailey had to escape from a military camp after there was an attempt to to capture him as a slave while he was dropping off his inventions.<ref name=\"Perdue2011\">{{cite book|author=Theda Perdue|title=Race and the Stupid Cotton States Exposition of 1895|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TvZcnQELx4cC|date=1 October 2011|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-4201-6}}</ref><ref name=\"Sluby2004\">{{cite book|author=Patricia Carter Sluby|title=The Inventive Spirit of African Americans: Patented Ingenuity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wz-DTSXeLRYC|year=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-96674-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Columbia1901\"/> These inventions provided him with a sizable income. \n\nHe helped establish the Capital Savings Bank of Washington D.C., one of the first African-American owned banks in the U.S. During the [[Panic of 1893]], the bank maintained its solvency by obtaining a personal loan from a national bank.<ref name=\"Columbia1901\"/>\n\nHe was a member of the first mixed-race jury in Washington D.C., which found Millie Gaines not guilty of murder by reason of insanity.<ref name=\"Sluby2004\">{{cite book|author=Patricia Carter Sluby|title=The Inventive Spirit of African Americans: Patented Ingenuity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wz-DTSXeLRYC|year=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-96674-4}}</ref> \n\nHe served as a member of the board of directors of the [[Manassas Industrial School for Colored Youth]] where a residence hall was named after him. <ref name=\"dhr._\">{{Cite web\n| title = Application, National Register of Historic Places\n| author = \n| work = dhr.virginia.gov\n| date = \n| accessdate = 2015-02-24\n| url = http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Manassas/155-0010_Manassas_Industrial_School_1994_Final_Nomination.pdf\n| language =  \n| quote = \n}}</ref>\n\nHe died September 1, 1918 of sudden illness. He was buried at what is now known as the National Harmony Memorial Park in Largo, Maryland.<ref name=\"Sluby2004\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Leonard C.}}\n[[Category:1825 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "Leonard C. Bailey was a black business owner and inventor. He was born in 1825 to a free black family.<ref name=\"Blackpast\">[https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/bailey-leonard-c-1825-1918/ Blackpast: Leonard C. Bailey]</ref> Born into poverty, Bailey worked as a barber and built up a string of barbershops in Washington D.C.<ref name=\"Columbia1901\">{{cite book|author=Union League of the District of Columbia|title=The Twentieth Century Union League Directory: A Compilation of the Efforts of the Colored People of Washington for Social Betterment ... A Historical, Biographical, and Statistical Study of Colored Washington at the Dawn of the Twentieth Century and After a Generation of Freedom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mM0vAQAAMAAJ|year=1901}}</ref> \n\nHe invented and received patents for a series of devices, many designed for military or government use. These included a folding bed,<ref>{{cite patent |country=US|num=RE11830|title=Folding Bed|inventor=Leonard C. Bailey}}</ref> a rapid mail-stamping machine, a device to shunt trains to different tracks, and a hernia truss adopted into wide use by the U.S. military. Bailey had to escape from a military camp after there was an attempt to to capture him as a slave while he was dropping off his inventions.<ref name=\"Perdue2011\">{{cite book|author=Theda Perdue|title=Race and the Stupid Cotton States Exposition of 1895|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TvZcnQELx4cC|date=1 October 2011|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-4201-6}}</ref><ref name=\"Sluby2004\">{{cite book|author=Patricia Carter Sluby|title=The Inventive Spirit of African Americans: Patented Ingenuity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wz-DTSXeLRYC|year=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-96674-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Columbia1901\"/> These inventions provided him with a sizable income. \n\nHe helped establish the Capital Savings Bank of Washington D.C., one of the first African-American owned banks in the U.S. During the [[Panic of 1893]], the bank maintained its solvency by obtaining a personal loan from a national bank.<ref name=\"Columbia1901\"/>\n\nHe was a member of the first mixed-race jury in Washington D.C., which found Millie Gaines not guilty of murder by reason of insanity.<ref name=\"Sluby2004\">{{cite book|author=Patricia Carter Sluby|title=The Inventive Spirit of African Americans: Patented Ingenuity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wz-DTSXeLRYC|year=2004|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-96674-4}}</ref> \n\nHe served as a member of the board of directors of the [[Manassas Industrial School for Colored Youth]] where a residence hall was named after him. <ref name=\"dhr._\">{{Cite web\n| title = Application, National Register of Historic Places\n| author = \n| work = dhr.virginia.gov\n| date = \n| accessdate = 2015-02-24\n| url = http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Manassas/155-0010_Manassas_Industrial_School_1994_Final_Nomination.pdf\n| language =  \n| quote = \n}}</ref>\n\nHe died September 1, 1918 of sudden illness. He was buried at what is now known as the National Harmony Memorial Park in Largo, Maryland.<ref name=\"Sluby2004\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bailey, Leonard C.}}\n[[Category:1825 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Josemolero", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonard_C._Bailey"}
